Upstream bug: location state never reaches the shell after startup. The Go
core's generic `subscribe` fan-out (core/internal/server/server.go) forwards
every service EXCEPT "location" -- there is no shouldSubscribe("location")
block, so the QML's subscribe-all event socket never receives location
pushes (only a dedicated `location.subscribe` stream would, and nothing in
the QML tree opens one). LocationService.qml therefore relies on a single
`location.getState` pull at connect time (~3 s after core start) -- but the
core can't have a GeoClue2 fix that early: NewClient seeds an IP-derived
location and the real WiFi fix lands only after the client's 10 s
TimeThreshold, i.e. the pull always races and always loses. Net effect:
weather is pinned to the IP-geolocated city (ISP egress, not the machine)
for the whole session. Fix: poll getState on a 30 s timer; the added
same-coords guard in handleStateUpdate keeps unchanged polls from
re-emitting locationChanged (which would refetch weather and re-hit the
reverse-geocoding services every tick). Verified against
AvengeMedia/DankMaterialShell@74896fb87cb9e4bb866dbabcfd754e3e649ad0c7.
--- a/Services/LocationService.qml
+++ b/Services/LocationService.qml
@@ -20,6 +20,13 @@
             getState();
     }

+    Timer {
+        running: root.locationAvailable
+        interval: 30000
+        repeat: true
+        onTriggered: root.getState()
+    }
+
     Connections {
         target: DMSService

@@ -36,6 +43,9 @@
         if (lat === 0 && lon === 0)
             return;

+        if (lat === root.latitude && lon === root.longitude)
+            return;
+
         root.latitude = lat;
         root.longitude = lon;
         root.locationChanged(data);
